caption: I didn't say I would help.  I said I'd accompany you.
Our next song is dedicated to a special someone who decided not to take the family to his in-law’s Florida timeshare.
If I had a shovel, I’d shovel in the morning, I’d shovel in the evening all over this town...
Look at us!  Both enjoying our Christmas gifts to each other.
Ooo. I've got another one... "There's snow business like snow business..."
Remember when you said, 'WE spent a tough ten hours in labor?" Well, now WE'RE shoveling the snow.
Hello sidewalk, my old friend...
Now you know how I feel when you help in the kitchen.
This one's about a man who wouldn't buy a snowblower.
I never said I'd help, just that I'd accompany you.
Can you believe Nancy traded me this guitar for the snow blower?
Ice, ice, baby.
If I had a shovel, I'd shovel in the mor-mor-ning
Shovel 16 tons and what do you get?  Another bad shoulder and gloves are all wet.
Let me know when you're ready to pick up the tempo!
You asked me to accompany you.
Try to stay with the beat, Harold.
He’ll be shoveling around the corner when he comes!!! He’ll be shoveling....
And now, a traditional song from Hawaii, for which there are plenty of bargain flights and nice hotels.
Oh, you’re cold and tired?  Hold on, let me get my violin.

Sorry, I don't know "Drop Dead, Glenda." 
Could you maybe hum a few bars
Michael, blow the snow next door.  Hallelujah!
Oh,give me a home...in a temperate zone....
I'll pick while you shovel.
And my next number is a little tune I picked up in Florida just before you decided to move us back to Vermont
Any other requests besides 'Karen, Grab a Damn Shovel'?
I like that we do things together.
I look at the drive and I see it needs shoveling.  Still my guitar gently weeps.
This next one goes out to the hardest working man in snow business.
Ninety-nine shovels of snow on the ground, ninety-nine shovels of snow . . . you scoop one up and give it a chuck, ninety-eight shovels of snow on the ground.
